            <p>1906 Indiana Ave.<lb/>
                Chicago&#44; May 23&#44; 1889.<lb/></p>
            <p>The Rev. Dr. S. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#58;&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Permit me to return in the name of my dear mother and<lb/> also for myself&#44; heartfelt thanks to you for your kind words<lb/> conveying your sympathy to us in our bereavement.  Coming from a<lb/> man who differs so widely from the views held and taught by our<lb/> sainted father&#44; your lines were doubly gratifying and were a<lb/> soothing balm to our wound.  However widely you diverged in<lb/> religious matters from the departed&#44; one trait of character I hold<lb/> you have in common with him&#58; unswerving consistency to the right<lb/> as understood by you.  Your recognition of father&#39;s kindness<lb/> honors both him to whose memory <sic>you</sic> words were consecrated&#44; and him<lb/> whose pen voiced the sentiment.  Believe me&#44; Honored Sir&#44; to be<lb/> forever<lb/> Gratefully yours&#44;<lb/> Emil G. Hirsch<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
